The Epicureans admitted the reality of motion and the existence of void ; Melissus took the other horn of the dilemma and, denying the existence of void, sought to show therefrom the impossibility of motion. His reasoning is interesting. ‘⁴ Every movement presupposes a void3 that which can receive another into itself is void; that which cannot receive another is full ; that which moves can do so only in the void. But the void would be non-existent, and the non-existent does not exist. Consequently there is no void, therefore no motion.’' See Zeller, ‘Prae-Socratic Philosophy,’ i. 635.
